\section{Crystal structure of dicesium hydrogen citrate from laboratory single-crystal and powder X-ray diffraction data and DFT comparison}
${ }^{a}$ Atlantic International University, Honolulu HI , USA, ${ }^{\text {b} D e p a r t m e n t ~ o f ~ C h e m i s t r y, ~ N o r t h w e s t e r n ~ U n i v e r s i t y, ~ E v a n s t o n ~ I L, ~}$ USA, and 'Illinois Institute of Technology, Department of Chemistry, 3101 S. Dearborn St., Chicago IL 60616, USA.

*Correspondence e-mail: \href{mailto:kaduk@polycrystallography.com}{kaduk@polycrystallography.com}

The crystal structure of dicesium hydrogen citrate, $2 \mathrm{Cs}^{+}$. $\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{6} \mathrm{O}_{7}^{2-}$, has been solved using laboratory $\mathrm{X}$-ray single-crystal diffraction data, refined using laboratory powder X-ray data, and optimized using density functional techniques. The $\mathrm{Cs}^{+}$cation is nine-coordinate, with a bond-valence sum of $0.92$ valence units. The $\mathrm{CsO}_{9}$ coordination polyhedra share edges and corners to form a three-dimensional framework. The citrate anion is located on a mirror plane. Its central hydroxy/carboxylate $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \cdots \mathrm{O}$ hydrogen bond is short, and (unusually) intermolecular. The centrosymmetric end-end carboxylate hydrogen bond is exceptionally short $(\mathrm{O} \cdots \mathrm{O}=2.416 \AA$ ) and strong. These hydrogen bonds contribute $16.5$ and $21.7 \mathrm{kcal} \mathrm{mol}^{-1}$, respectively, to the crystal energy. The hydrophobic methylene groups occupy pockets in the framework.

\section{Chemical context}
In the course of a systematic study of the crystal structures of group 1 (alkali metal) citrate salts to understand the anion's conformational flexibility, ionization, coordination tendencies, and hydrogen bonding, we have determined several new crystal structures. Most of the new structures were solved using X-ray powder diffraction data (laboratory and/or synchrotron), but single crystals were used where available. The general trends and conclusions about the sixteen new compounds and twelve previously determined structures are being reported separately (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2017a). Eleven of the new structures - $\mathrm{NaKHC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, $\mathrm{NaK}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}, \quad \mathrm{Na}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}, \quad \mathrm{NaH}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}, \quad \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}, \mathrm{Rb}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}, \quad \mathrm{Rb}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right), \quad \mathrm{Rb}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, $\mathrm{Na}_{5} \mathrm{H}\left(\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\right)_{2}$, and $\mathrm{CsH}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ - have been published recently (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2016a,b,c,d,e, 2017b,c,d,e,f, Rammohan et al., 2016), and two additional structures $\mathrm{KH}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ and $\mathrm{KH}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{2}$ - have been communicated to the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD) (Kaduk $\&$ Stern, 2016a,b). We report here synthesis and crystal structure of another alkali metal citrate salt, $2 \mathrm{Cs}^{+} \cdot \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}{ }^{2-}$.

\section{Structural commentary}
The asymmetric unit of the title compound is shown in Fig. 1. The root-mean-square deviation of the non-hydrogen atoms in the experimentally determined and in the DFT-optimized structures is $0.098 \AA$ (Fig. 2). The largest differences are $0.13 \AA$, at $\mathrm{Cs} 19$ and $\mathrm{O} 11$. This good agreement provides strong evidence that the experimentally determined structure is correct (van de Streek \& Neumann, 2014). The following discussion uses the DFT-optimized structure.

