\section{Supramolecular features}
The $\mathrm{CsO}_{9}$ coordination polyhedra share edges and corners to form a three-dimensional framework (Fig. 3). The central hydroxy/carboxylate $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \cdots \mathrm{O}$ hydrogen $\mathrm{O} 17-\mathrm{H} 18 \cdots \mathrm{O} 16$ is short, and (unusually) intermolecular. The centrosymmetric end-end $\mathrm{O} 12-\mathrm{H} 20-\mathrm{O} 12$ hydrogen bond (with H20 situated on an inversion center) is exceptionally short and strong (Table 1). By the correlation of Rammohan \& Kaduk (2017a), these hydrogen bonds contribute $16.5$ and $21.7 \mathrm{kcal} \mathrm{mol}^{-1}$ to the crystal energy. The hydrophobic methylene groups occupy pockets in the framework (Fig. 3).

