\section{Database survey}
Details of the comprehensive literature search for citrate structures are presented in Rammohan \& Kaduk (2017a). A reduced cell search of the cell of dicesium hydrogen citrate in the Cambridge Structural Database (Groom et al., 2016) (increasing the default tolerance from $1.5$ to $2.0 \%$ ) yielded 100 hits, but combining the cell search with the elements C, H, Cs, and $\mathrm{O}$ only yielded no hits.

\section{Synthesis and crystallization}
Citric acid monohydrate, $\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right), \quad$ (2.0796 g, $10.0 \mathrm{mmol})$ was dissolved in $20 \mathrm{ml}$ deionized water. $\mathrm{Cs}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ (3.2582 g, $10.0 \mathrm{mmol}$, Sigma-Aldrich) was added to the citric acid solution slowly with stirring. The resulting clear colourless solution was evaporated to dryness in a $333 \mathrm{~K}$ oven. Single crystals were isolated from the colourless solid.

\section{Refinement}
A single crystal was mounted in inert oil and transferred to the cold gas stream of a Bruker Kappa APEX CCD area detector system equipped with a $\mathrm{Cu} \mathrm{K} \alpha$ sealed tube with $\mathrm{MX}$ optics. Despite suggestions from multiple programs that the space group was Pnma, all attempts to refine the structure in this space group yielded unreasonable disorder and non-positivedefinite displacement coefficients. Presumably the poor crystal quality and/or twinning were the source of the problems. The best refinement using single crystal data was obtained using space group $P 2_{1} 2_{1} 2_{1}$.

A portion of the sample was ground in a mortar and pestle, and blended with NIST SRM 640b silicon internal standard. The powder pattern indicated that the sample contained about $24 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{CsHC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2017f), which was included as phase 2 in the refinement. The $\mathrm{Si}$ internal standard was included as phase 3 .

